## Kernel architecture

* original interactive version at <http://www.makelinux.net/>
  
  ```
              | SYSTEM         | NETWORKING     | STORAGE        | MEMORY         | PROCESSING
              |                |                |                |                |
  User Space  | system         | Sockets        | Virtual        | Virtual        | Process:
  Interfaces  | calls          |                | file system    | Memory         | execution
  and Virtual |                |                |                |                | and resources
  Subsystems  |                |                |                |                |
              |                |               NFS              mmap            process
              |                |                |                |              memory
              |                |                |                |                |
  internal    | proc, sysfs    | Protocols      | Logical        |                | Tasks
  subsystems  | filesystems    | TCP,UDP,IP     | file systems   |                |
              |                | skb            | ext4, XFS,...  |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
  inter-      |                |                |                |                |
  operability |                |                |              cache              |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
  HW          | Device Model,  | Network        | Block          | Memory         | Scheduler
  abstraction | modules        | Management     | Device         | Manager:       |
              |                |                |  |             | kmalloc        |
              |                |                |  +- Virtual    |                |
              |                |                |     Block devs.|                |
              |                |                |               swap              |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
  HW          | Bus            | Network        | Disk           | Memory access: | Interrupts
  dependent   | drivers        | drivers        | Drivers        | Pages, Faults  |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
              |                |                |                |                |
  HW          | Uus            |  Network cards:| Disk           | MMU, RAM       | CPU, registers
              | Uontrollers    |  Ethernet      | controllers:   |                |
              | UCI, USB       |                | IDE, SCSI      |                |
  ```

## Storage Stack Diagram
i[data:image/png;base64,]

## Cache (Pages)

- Cache Page: transparently cache disk data for future requests 
  improving I/O performance.
- Linux kernel is designed to use as much RAM as it can to cache information
  from your local and remote filesystems and disks.
- cache is not reclaimed at the time when process get stop/exit,
  however when the other processes requires more memory than,
  the kernel will run heuristics to reclaim the memory by storing
  any pending-to-write cache data and allocating that memory to
  new process.
- When any kind of file/data is requested, the kernel will look
  for a copy of the part of the file the user is acting on, and,
  if no such copy exists, it will allocate one new page of cache
  memory and fill it with the appropriate contents read out from
  (hardware|network) storage.
- SysV shared memory segments are also accounted as a cache, though they
  do not represent any data on the disks.

## Cache vs Buffers
* Buffers are the disk block representation of the data that is stored under
  the page caches. Buffers contains the metadata of the files/data which
  resides under the page cache. Example: When there is a request of any data
  which is present in the page cache, first the kernel checks the data in the
  buffers which contain the metadata which points to the actual files/data
  contained in the page caches. Once from the metadata the actual block address
  of the file is known, it is picked up by the kernel for processing.

## Memory Manager (kmalloc)

* Slub allocator:
 <http://resources.infosecinstitute.com/exploiting-linux-kernel-heap-corruptions-slub-allocator/>

## Scheduler
- Shares CPU between tasks.
- Selects next task to run (on each CPU) when:
  - Running task terminates.
  - Running task sleeps (waiting for an event)
  - A new task created or sleeping task wakes up
  - Running task's timeslice is over

- Goals:
  - Be "fair"
  - Timeslice based on task priority
  - Low task reponse time
  - High (task completion) throughput
  - Balance load among CPUs
  - Power efficient
  - Low overhead of running scheduler's code

- Works with mainframes, servers, destkops/laptops, embedded/phones.

Current Scheduler design (2.6.23+ Ingo Molnar, 2007)
- Scheduling policies within scheduling classes.
- Scheduling class with higher priority served first.
- Task can migrate between CPUs, scheduling polices and scheduling classes.

Scheduling classes and policies:
```
* Stop                  Highest priority class : Can preempt everything and is preempted by nothing
  - No policy
* Deadline              Highest priority tasks in the system
  - SCHED_DEADLINE
* Real Time             POSIX "real-time" tasks. Priorities 0-99
  - SCHED_FIFO
  - SCHED_RR
* Fair                  Tracks virtual runtime of tasks (amount of time run)
  - SCHED_NORMAL
  - SCHED_BATCH
  - SCHED_IDLE
* Idle                  Lowest priority class. One kernel thread (idle) per CPU
  - No policy            Runs only when nothing else is runnable on a CPU.
                         Can take the CPU to low power state
```

## Virtme: kernel developers' best friend

* <https://www.collabora.com/news-and-blog/blog/2018/09/18/virtme-the-kernel-developers-best-friend/>

By Ezequiel Garcia 2018-09-18

... testing via QEMU is pretty common...  QEMU can be hard to setup,

... this time we want to take a somewhat different path and explore virtme,
which is basically a QEMU wrapper.

> Virtme is a set of simple tools to run a virtualized Linux kernel 
> that uses the host Linux distribution or a simple rootfs instead of a
> whole disk image. Virtme is tiny, easy to use, and makes testing 
> kernel changes quite simple.

### Installing virtme

  ```
  $ git clone https://github.com/ezequielgarcia/virtme.git
  $ cd virtme
  $ sudo ./setup.py install

  #  get your favourite kernel tree
  $ git clone git://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git
  $ virtme-configkernel --defconfig

  # Enable the drivers you need. Example vim2m (virtual video4linux memory2memory virtual driver)
  + CONFIG_MEDIA_SUPPORT=y
  + CONFIG_MEDIA_CAMERA_SUPPORT=y
  + CONFIG_VIDEO_DEV=y
  + CONFIG_VIDEO_V4L2=y
  + CONFIG_V4L2_MEM2MEM_DEV=y
  + CONFIG_V4L_TEST_DRIVERS=y
  + CONFIG_VIDEO_VIM2M=y

  $ make -j4                                   # build new kernel

  $ virtme-run --kimg arch/x86_64/boot/bzImage # alt 1. Run virtme
  $ virtme-run --kdir .                        # alt 2. == alt 1.
  $ virtme-run --kdir . \ 
    --script-dir test-dir/                     # alt 3. Run script at boot
  
  ```

...  In the next blog post we'll see an example of virtme in action, 
  testing bleeding-edge gstreamer builds on bleeding-edge kernels. Stay 
  tuned!

## Debugfs

* <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debugfs>
 Unlike /proc, which is only meant for information about a process, 
or sysfs, which has strict one-value-per-file rules, debugfs has no 
rules at all. Developers can put any information they want there.[4]

##  OpenWall
* <https://www.openwall.com/>

OpenWall solicit ayuda para crear un mdulo de seguridad para 
observar kernels de Linux en busca de actividad sospechosa.

En la explicacin de la compaa, el Kernel Runtime Guard (LKRG) de 
Linux se describe como un mdulo que intenta detectar y responder 
oportunamente a modificaciones no autorizadas en el ncleo Linux en 
ejecucin (comprobacin de integridad) o credenciales (como ID de 
usuario) de los procesos en ejecucin (deteccin de exploits) .

Desarrollado por Adam Zabrocki (@ adam_pi3) y ahora defendido por 
OpenWall, el primer corte del cdigo lleg la semana pasada.


* Linux Kernel Runtime Guard es un LKM que detecta los exploits de kernel
  <http://www.openwall.com/lkrg/>

* Es imperfecto por ahora y OpenWall lo admite: Mientras que LKRG 
  soluciona muchas vulnerabilidades preexistentes del Kernel de Linux, 
  probablemente derrotar a muchos exploits futuros (incluso de 
  vulnerabilidades an desconocidas) que no intentan especficamente 
  eludir el LKRG (aunque a veces a expensas de exploits ms complicados 
  y/o menos confiables) .

* La wiki de LKRG explica que funciona calculando hashes de regiones 
  de Kernel, secciones y estructuras importantes frente a los hashes 
  de la base de datos interna.

* Idealmente, LKRG debera ejecutarse en un sistema de limpieza 
  conocida (es decir, despus de haber arrancado una instalacin 
  completamente nueva); crea su base de datos confiable de hashes 
  contra ese entorno, y usa esos hash para observar los cambios.

* Como este es un primer corte del LKRG (como es la versin 0.0), hay 
  una lista de cosas por hacer sustancial. Actualmente, cubre datos 
  crticos de CPU/core para las arquitecturas x86 y amd64; la seccin 
  Linux Kernel .text (las notas dicen Esto cubre casi [01_PM.TODO] el 
  kernel de Linux en s, como tablas de syscall, todos los 
  procedimientos, todas las funciones, todos los manejadores de IRQ, 
  etc.), la tabla de excepcin del Kernel de Linux, de solo lectura de 
  la seccin de datos, las asignaciones de E/S de IOMMU y los mdulos 
  cargados.

* OpenWall dijo que LKRG ha sido probado en varios escenarios, y al 
mismo tiempo, toma nota de los tipos de limitaciones que se aplican:

* En nuestras pruebas en ncleos de distribucin vulnerables, LKRG 
  detect con xito ciertos exploits preexistentes de CVE-2014-9322 
  (BadIRET), CVE-2017-5123 (waitid (2) falta de access_ok), 
  CVE-2017-6074 (use-after- free en el protocolo DCCP). Sin embargo, no 
  se esperara que se detecten exploits de CVE-2016-5195 (Dirty COW), 
  ya que aquellos se dirigen directamente al espacio de usuario incluso 
  si es a travs del Kernel .

* Fuzzing the linux kenrel entry code.

* <https://blogs.oracle.com/linux/fuzzing-the-linux-kernel-x86-entry-code,-part-1-of-3>

If you've been following Linux kernel development or system call 
fuzzing at all, then you probably know about trinity and syzkaller. 
These programs have uncovered many kernel bugs over the years. The 
way they work is basically throwing random system calls at the kernel 
in the hope that some of them will crash the kernel or otherwise 
trigger a detectable fault (e.g. a buffer overflow) in the kernel 
code.

While these fuzzers effectively test the system calls themselves (and 
the code reachable through system calls), one thing they don't test 
very well is what happens at the actual transition point between 
userspace and the kernel. There is more to this boundary than meets 
the eye; it is written in assembly code and there is a lot of 
architectural state (CPU state) that must be verified or sanitized 
before the kernel can safely start executing its C code.

This blog post explores how one might go about writing a fuzzer 
targeting the Linux kernel entry code on x86.

  Steven Rostedt, Open Source Programmer at VMware, maintains the Real Time
Stable releases of the Linux kernel, among other things. Rostedt is one of
the original developers of the PREEMPT_RT patch and began working on it in
2004 with the goal of turning Linux into a real-time designed operating system
. He is also the main author, developer, and maintainer of Ftrace, a tool
designed to help developers find what is going on inside the kernel.
According to the Ftrace wiki, the tool can be used for debugging or analyzing
latencies and performance issues that take place outside of user-space.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pIJ3Zv_uxn0

## Linux out of memory killer

OOM kill is a mechanism called used to recover memory on a system.
... allows killing a single task (called also oom victim) while 
that task will terminate in a reasonable time and thus free up memory.

 When OOM killer does its job we can find indications about that by 
searching the logs (like /var/log/messages and grepping for 
Killed). If you want to configure the OOM killer I suggest 
reading the following link https://lnkd.in/dfFYJAA4. It is important 
to understand that the OOM killer chooses between processes based on 
the oom_score. If you want to see the value for a specific process 
we can just read /proc/[PID]/oom_score - as shown in the screenshot 
below. If we want to alter the score we can do it using 
/proc/[PID]/oom_score_adj - as shown also in the screenshot below. 
The valid range is from 0 (never kill) to 1000 (always kill), the 
lower the value is the lower is the probability the process will be 
killed. For more information, please read https://lnkd.in/dT_xfYsn. 
In the next writeup I am going to elaborate about the kernel thread 
oom_reaper. See you in my next writeup ;-)You can follow me on 
twitter - @boutnaru (https://lnkd.in/dkYSgHHZ). Also, you can read my 
other writeups on medium - https://lnkd.in/drU__sCj #Linux #Memory 
#MemoryManagement #OOMKiller #OutOfMemory

## Zswap linux

* <https://www.linkedin.com/posts/shlomi-boutnaru-ba781811a_linux-kernel-memorymanagement-activity-6990403402895667200-gkCm>

* zswap is a backend for frontswap.
* Frontswap provides a transcendent memory interface for swap pages. 
* In some cases we can get increased performance by saving swapped pages
  in RAM (or a RAM-like device) and not on disk as swap partition\swapfile
  (https://lnkd.in/dfXuA6qV). [[{scalability.memory.zswap}]]
* The frontends are usually implemented in the kernel while the backend is 
  implemented as a kernel module (as we will show soon).
* zswap trades CPU cycles for potentially reduced swap I/O.
* A significant performance improvement can happen in case the reads from 
  the swap device are much slower than the reads from the compressed cache.
* zswap_frontswap_store function attempts to compress and store a single page
* kernel thread zswap-shrink is created created based on a workqueue
  (https://lnkd.in/dw82QKeD). 
* For more information like the compression used by zswap (the default one is lzo)
  and other parameters that can be configured for zswap I suggest reading the 
  <https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Zswap>
* You can also read the parameter ons /sys/module/zswap/parameters

[[{scalability.cache.bmc-cache]]
## bmc-cache: In-kernel memcache up to 18x throughput

* <https://github.com/Orange-OpenSource/bmc-cache>
* BMC (BPF Memory Cache) is an in-kernel cache for memcached on top of
  eBPF.
* It enables runtime, crash-safe extension of the Linux kernel to 
  process specific memcached requests before the execution of the 
  standard network stack.
* BMC does not require modification of neither the Linux kernel
  nor the memcached application. Running memcached with BMC
  improves throughput by up to 18x compared to the vanilla 
  memcached application.
[[scalability.cache.bmc-cache}]]

## Linux kernel New API (NAPI)

* <https://wiki.linuxfoundation.org/networking/napi>
* <https://www.linkedin.com/posts/shlomi-boutnaru-ba781811a_linux-networking-interrupts-activity-7070457316214489089-yl4q>

"New API" or NAPI is used to reduce the number of received interrupts.

Think of Gigabit network drivers receiving large number of packets at a fast pace.
(https://www.hitchhikersguidetolearning.com/2023/04/09/handling-receive-packets-via-napi/)
(~90K interrupts/sec)

NAPI does not break backward compatibility.  "NAPI" is a kernel thread 
which is created using the kthread_run() function 
... NAPI combines hardware interrupts and polling.
[[}]]

## Good Book on Linux Memory Management and File Systems

(Frdric YhuelFrdric Yhuel  1st) I would love to find a Linux 
textbook equivalent to the excellent Egor Rogov's PostgreSQL 14 
Internals. Linux is bigger project, but I'm particulary interested in 
memory management and file systems.

For example, I'd like to understand exactly what happens when we want 
to increase the huge pages pool (with sysctl vm.nr_hugepages=N), and 
there's not enough contigous free memory available.
Is there a direct reclaim followed by a direct compaction?

* By the way, how do kcompactd and khugepaged work together?
* Don't they overlap in some way?

... Things like that. I'm not sure if such a book exists... but if 
you happen to know of one, please let me know!
